-- Rebar Rises for Second Day as Moving Average Signals Rebound
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-03-20T03:21:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-20/rebar-rises-for-second-day-as-moving-average-signals-rebound.html
Steel reinforcement-bar futures
climbed for a second day as a rally above a technical level
strengthened investor sentiment.  Rebar for delivery in October on the Shanghai Futures
Exchange gained as much as 0.7 percent to 3,868  yuan  ($623) a
metric ton before trading at 3,863 at 11:11 a.m. local time. The
contract dropped to a three-month low of 3,741 yuan on March 14
and declined 3.1 percent this year.  The sell-off in the building material paused yesterday and
prices closed above the five-day moving average, signaling that
rates may rise in the short-term, Shenyin & Wanguo Futures Co.,
said in a report today.  “Weak fundamentals haven’t changed in the market but the
from a technical point of view, the futures’ rally above a five-
day moving average aligned the market in a bullish pattern in
the short term,” said the report.  Iron ore  for immediate delivery fell 0.2 percent to $134.40
a ton yesterday, according to data compiled by The Steel Index
Ltd. The  average spot price  of rebar retreated 0.2 percent
yesterday to 3,686 yuan, according to data from Beijing Antaike
Information Development Co.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
